            "content": {
                "raw": "Hi Miguel, thanks for issuing this pull request.  The sunrise exporter and some of the other modifications are very useful and valuable to the codebase.  Unfortunately, as it stands, I'm going to formally decline it at this time.  If you are willing to submit multiple pull requests for each of the different components, I think it would be considerably easier to comment for stylistic and algorithmic content, and I am happy to help you to create multiple pull requests so that this can happen.\n\nThe principle issues which are concerning here:\n\n * This PR contains multiple pieces of independent functionality, each of which needs to be reviewed in detail.\n * The code base has diverged *considerably* since this was under development, and integrating it would be non-trivial.\n * All new functionality is completely untested in this PR.\n * The streaming system is largely unrelated to yt and would be better suited to be an independent package.\n * This breaks backward compatibility with existing code that uses Rockstar.\n\nAgain, I think that reviewing this on its own merits as a series of smaller pull requests would be considerably easier, and may lead to some or all of it being included, but as it stands, this is not suitable for inclusion.\n\nOne remaining note that I wanted to make is that this is a good amount of work which seems to have been done in total isolation from the rest of the yt development community; some of the design decisions are relatively sweeping and should be subject to YTEP documents or at the bare minimum a discussion on the mailing list, but this PR has evolved almost completely independently.  While this is certainly within the scope of how development in open source can function, it's also very difficult to then integrate that work into the primary repository for the code, which means that the fork will not benefit from other performance improvements or bug fixes.  It also means that people using the mainline version of yt will be unable to benefit from your improvements and hard work.\n",
                "html": "<p>Hi Miguel, thanks for issuing this pull request.  The sunrise exporter and some of the other modifications are very useful and valuable to the codebase.  Unfortunately, as it stands, I'm going to formally decline it at this time.  If you are willing to submit multiple pull requests for each of the different components, I think it would be considerably easier to comment for stylistic and algorithmic content, and I am happy to help you to create multiple pull requests so that this can happen.</p>\n<p>The principle issues which are concerning here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>This PR contains multiple pieces of independent functionality, each of which needs to be reviewed in detail.</li>\n<li>The code base has diverged <em>considerably</em> since this was under development, and integrating it would be non-trivial.</li>\n<li>All new functionality is completely untested in this PR.</li>\n<li>The streaming system is largely unrelated to yt and would be better suited to be an independent package.</li>\n<li>This breaks backward compatibility with existing code that uses Rockstar.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Again, I think that reviewing this on its own merits as a series of smaller pull requests would be considerably easier, and may lead to some or all of it being included, but as it stands, this is not suitable for inclusion.</p>\n<p>One remaining note that I wanted to make is that this is a good amount of work which seems to have been done in total isolation from the rest of the yt development community; some of the design decisions are relatively sweeping and should be subject to YTEP documents or at the bare minimum a discussion on the mailing list, but this PR has evolved almost completely independently.  While this is certainly within the scope of how development in open source can function, it's also very difficult to then integrate that work into the primary repository for the code, which means that the fork will not benefit from other performance improvements or bug fixes.  It also means that people using the mainline version of yt will be unable to benefit from your improvements and hard work.</p>",
                "markup": "markdown"
            },
